53
00:04:05,908 --> 00:04:10,880
First is top-coding,
which involves restricting the upper

54
00:04:10,880 --> 00:04:15,790
range of a variable that may identify
outliers or unique individuals.

55
00:04:16,840 --> 00:04:19,510
Second is collapsing or combining.

56
00:04:19,510 --> 00:04:24,400
Where you combine values into a single
variable or merging data from two or

57
00:04:24,400 --> 00:04:28,070
more variables into one summary variable.

58
00:04:28,070 --> 00:04:32,770
Third is sampling, where you release
a randomized sample of the larger

59
00:04:32,770 --> 00:04:37,470
original data set that provides analysis
results comparable to the original.

60
00:04:38,600 --> 00:04:44,470
Fourth is swapping, where you use an
indirect identifier to match unique cases.

61
00:04:44,470 --> 00:04:48,610
Then swapping values of key
variables between those cases.

62
00:04:48,610 --> 00:04:51,410
And finally, there is disturbing the data.

63
00:04:51,410 --> 00:04:55,420
Where you manipulate the data
by adding random variation in

64
00:04:55,420 --> 00:04:58,680
the value while maintaining
their statistical properties.

65
00:04:59,770 --> 00:05:03,880
When it comes to qualitative data,
